		   <table class="mform"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform" valign="top" id="forumSubject">GUIDE:  Increasing Performance on min-spec systems<br clear="all" /><script type="text/javascript">document.title = document.title + ": Thread: GUIDE:  Increasing Performance on min-spec systems";</script>
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Mon, Feb 21st 2:29 AM2005 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a href="/forum.html?forum=21&mid=1108970919146539277&post=1"><a class="sm" href="/forum.html?forum=21&mid=1108970919146539277&post=1&replyto=1108970919146539277"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=1108970919146539277></a></small>| <span id="fs8">Edited: 2005-03-08 05:59:03</span></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=295789"><span id=Scholar>oberonqa the Irrelevant</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />801 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=oberonqa&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>As we're all painfully aware, the minimum requirements for World of Warcraft is a joke.&nbsp;&nbsp;It is my personal opinion that the QA department of Blizzard Entertainment be burned down for ever giving the green-light on the minimum requirements.  They are misleading and sometimes downright wrong.<br><br>So what do you do if your one of the individuals stuck playing the game on a min-spec system?  I know a lot of you have considered throwing your computer out the window (especially when your in Ironforge getting .01 frames per second).  However, there is some hope for you.<br><br>It is the purpose of this guide to help people on min-spec systems to get the best gaming experience possible.  This guide is not meant for people who play the game on a computer equipped with a video card that is less than two years old, a processor that is at faster than 2.0Ghz, or 512MB+ of system RAM.<br><br><u>Standard Stuff</u><br><br>1.  Run Disk Defragmenter (Start -&gt; Accessories -&gt; System Tools -&gt; Disk Defragmenter) at least once a month.  I know this may seem a bit excessive, but it helps increase performance (this should be done anyway even if your not a WoW player).<br><br>2.  Turn off any programs that may be running in the background that are not essential to the running of your computer.  Given the limited resources you have available, it is important to make sure as much of those resources is free.  Turn off anti-virus software and firewall software for example.<br><br>3.  Download and run either Ad-Aware or Spybot Search and Destroy (I prefer using Spybot... but it isn't as user friendly).  Like Disk Defragmenter, this should be run at least once a month and should be run by everyone even if your not a WoW player.<br><br>4.  Run MSConfig (Start -&gt; Run -&gt; msconfig).  On the Startup Tab, uncheck any software that is not essential to the running of the computer.  Things like the Microsoft Office toolbar aren't required and should be disabled for example.  By doing this, you can minimize the number of programs/processes running in the background.<br><br><u>Video Drivers related</u><br><br>Look into changing your video card drivers over to the Omega Driver set.  This set of drivers is a custom driver set that has been designed for the purpose of actual gameplay rather than benchmark tests.  Using the Omega Drivers will not void your warrenty as long as you do not attempt to overclock the card.<br><br><u>WoW Startup option</u><br><br>I don't know if this actually does anything or not, but since I started using this switch, I have noticed a substantial (additional 8-10 FPS) increase in framerate.  It can't hurt by using it.<br><br>Right click on your World of Warcraft shortcut and add -notnl to the end of the &quot;target&quot; section.  It should look like this:<br><br><b>Before</b>:  &quot;&lt;drive&gt;\&lt;directory&gt;\WoW.exe&quot;<br><b>After</b>:  &quot;&lt;drive&gt;\&lt;directory&gt;\WoW.exe&quot; -notnl<br><br>&lt;drive&gt; is the drive World of Warcraft is installed in (example C:)<br>&lt;directory&gt; is the directory World of Warcraft is installed in (example World of Warcraft)<br><br>On my computer, the shortcut target is C:\World of Warcraft\<br><br>It is my belief that the tag -notnl disables Texturing and Lighting, which is resource-intensive.  Instead, by using this tag, it is my belief the game uses standard textures and default lighting (instead of dynamic lighting).  I could be mistaken and probably am... so please don't flame me.  All I know is I noticed a substantial increase in performance once I started using this tag.<br><br><u>Windowed Mode</u><br><br>Running the game in windowed mode can increase the frame rate by reducing the area of the screen that is rendered.  Running the game in full-screen mode looks great, but increases the load on the video card.  It's possible to get an extra 3-5 FPS running in windowed mode versus full screen mode.<br><br><u>Add-on's (contributed by Caj)</u><br><br>If you do use UIs try to get standalone version for the things you need rather than a package with a lot of extra fluff (ex. cosmos), this was probably the most noticeable change I've made performance wise. I went from Cosmos, Lootlink, and Gatherer to BottomBar, Sidebar, and Questfade (to get NPC and shared quests much faster) once I realized I never really used 99% of the stuff I was loading. <br><br><u>Windows Pagefile trick (submitted by Fenor)</u><br><br>*NOTE:**  This tweak can only be performed on a system that has 2 or more hard drives, not partitions on the same drive.<br>--------------------------------------------------------<br><br>Moving the pagefile away from your Windows drive is simple because: 1) WinXP is always hitting the hard drive to grab Windows and program files; and 2) WinXP is always hitting the hard drive to access the pagefile. So, step 1 must always wait for step 2 to finish before it can act, and vice versa. By placing the pagefile on a separate hard drive, your computer can access Windows, program files, and the pagefile, simultaneously. While doing this, you can also make sure the pagefile isn't fragmented and is sufficiently large.<br><br>To check to see if your pagefile is fragmented, right-click My Computer and choose Properties. Click the Advanced tab, the Settings button under Performance, the Advanced tab, and then the Change button under Virtual Memory. The Virtual Memory window is quite straightforward: You click a drive letter, set the paging file data, click Set, and reboot. So, for instance, suppose your Windows drive is E:, and you have a data drive of D:. Highlight D:, type values for the Initial Size (MB) and Maximum Size (MB) of the paging file (more on sizing in a moment), and then click Set. Then highlight E: and choose No Paging File, click OK at the warning message, and then click Set. Click OK in all the open dialog boxes and reboot.<br><br>How big should the paging file be? We've heard several theories, but the one that makes the most sense to us is to set the Initial Size (MB) to triple the amount of RAM you have (example: 512MB of RAM equals 1,500MB of initial pagefile size). Also, the Maximum Size (MB) should be two to three times the Initial Size (MB). Can you do without a pagefile, even if you have 1GB or 2GB of RAM? Yes, it works, but some applications and games won't work without there being some sort of pagefile, so you might as well set it correctly on the best drive you can.<br><br>Source:<br>Computer Power User (CPU) March 2005 • Vol.5 Issue 3 <br><br><u>ToMMTi-System Tools 3D Analyzer</u><br><br>I discovered this program when I tried to play the EQ2 trial.  While I was able to get the game to run using this tool, I can only recommend it for experienced users.  Additionally, it may be considered a hack by Blizzard, as it can be used to modify the way the game engine behaves (i.e. you can force the game to render everything in wireframes).  Use at your own risk!<br><br>If you choose to play around with this, follow the below instructions to get started:<br><br>1)  Click on the ToMMTi-System Tools 3D Analyzer link in the Useful Links section.<br><br>2)  At the top of the page, click on the Files link<br><br>3)  Click on the picture below the text &quot;ToMMTi-Systems Tools&quot;.  The picture is of the program 3D Analyzer (which is what you want).  This will download the file &quot;dontlinkthefile_3danalyzer-v236.exe&quot;.<br><br>4)  Once the file has finished downloading, run it and install it into the directory you installed World of Warcraft into.  Be sure the files are installed in the base directory (and not a subdirectory in the World of Warcraft folder).<br><br>5)  Run the file 3DAnalyze after the installation is complete (you can locate it in the base World of Warcraft directory).<br><br>6)  Click on the Select button in the upper left hand corner of the window.<br><br>7)  In the Open popup that appears, select WoW.exe and click on the Open button.<br><br>8)  Select any options you want (for information on what each option does, click on the text &quot;Click for Help&quot; located on the upper left-hand side of the window.  The help file is in English and German.<br><br>9)  When your ready, click on the Run button.<br><br>WARNING!!!!:  While use of this program shouldn't cause physical damage to your video card or other computer components, I cannot make any promises that it won't.  Additionally, it may be possible that use of this program may damage WoW files and/or inhibit the patching process.  If you use this program, <b>you use it at your own risk!</b>.  I mention it for the adventurous individuals among us who might consider this a challenge.  I will say that it does emulate Hardware TnL... so if you have a very old video card (like a Voodoo2 for example), you can use this program to emulate Hardware TnL and WoW will run with your video card.  But I must reiterate <b>use of this program is at your own risk!!!!</b><br><br><u>Useful Links</u><br><br><a href="HTTP://www.omegadrivers.net/" target="akztarg">Omega Drivers</a>: Custom Videocard drivers (works with all GeForce and Radeon cards)<br><a href="HTTP://www.safer-networking.org/en/index.html" target="akztarg">SpyBot: Search and Destroy</a>: Spyware/Adware removal tool<br><a href="HTTP://www.lavasoftusa.com/software/adaware/" target="akztarg">Ad-Aware</a>: Spyware/Adware removal tool<br><a href="HTTP://www.curse-gaming.com" target="akztarg">Curse-Gaming</a>: WoW Addon Database (submitted by Shinzero)<br><a href="HTTP://www.mlin.net/" target="akztarg">Mike Lins Homepage</a>:  Homepage for StartupControl Panel MSConfig-like program (submitted by CikrenaCT)<br><a href="HTTP://www.tommti-systems.de/start.html" target="akztarg">ToMMTi-System Tools 3D Analyzer</a>:  Program that lets you enable/disable 3D functions as well as general 3D card emulation (USE AT YOUR OWN RISK!!!!)<br><br><u>My Computer Specs</u><br><br>For point of conversation, here are my computer specs.  Before changing to the Omega Drivers, adding the &quot;-notnl&quot; tag and running in windowed mode, I would get about 9-11 FPS while wandering around in forests, 2-3 FPS while fighting, and .01-1 FPS while wandering around Ironforge and Stormwind.  After applying the changes, I get about 18-20 FPS while wandering around in forests, 11-15 FPS while fighting, and 5-9 FPS while wandering around Ironforge and Stormwind.<br><br>Intel Celeron 800Mhz with 66Mhz front-side bus<br>256MB SDRAM (PC-133)<br>Samsung DVD-CDRW Combo Drive<br>15GB 7500RPM Hard Drive<br>8GB 7500RPM Hard Drive<br>ATI Radeon 7500 PCI with 64MB RAM<br>SoundBlaster Live! X-Gamer 5.1 PCI<br>Linksys Wireless-G Network Card PCI<br>Windows XP Pro with Service Pack 2<br><br>Good luck and feel free to post your performance suggestions (aside from the obvious get a new computer or upgrade your current computer).<br><br><u>Revision History</u><br><br>2/25/05: Added Useful Links section and added contributions from Shinzero and Caj to the guide.<br>3/8/05:  Added contributions from Fenor and CikrenaCT to the guide.<br><br><i><span class="sm">Edited, Tue Feb 25 14:36:02 2005 by oberonqa</span class="sm"></i><br><br><i><span class="sm">Edited, Tue Mar  8 06:02:46 2005 by oberonqa</span class="sm"></i></p><br /><span class="sm">----------------------------</span><br /><u>WoW</u><br>-<a href="HTTP://wow.allakhazam.com/profile.html?35583" target="akztarg"> <b>Neocron</b></a>: Night Elf Warrior (Durotan - Outcastz Guild)<br>-<a href="HTTP://wow.allakhazam.com/profile.html?63424" target="akztarg"> <b>Taalin</b></a>: Tauren Shamen (Shadow Council - Unguilded)<br><br><u>FFXI</u><br>-<a href="HTTP://ffxi.allakhazam.com/profile.xml?77022" target="akztarg"> <b>Neocron</b></a>: San d'Orian Tarutaru BLM60/WHM30 (Gilgamesh Server - KoruptionINC LS)&nbsp;&nbsp;(Retired)<br><br><i>Fear is the mind killer</i></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from Somewhere.... just not sure WHERE</td><td align="right" id="fs8" >23 Replies</td></tr></table>
