		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.01]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=natsuko&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>I'd say run defrag WAY more than once a month. I don't know why but games like this really make drives fragmented sometimes.<br><br>This helped me a lot:<br><br>defrag c: -f<br>defrag d: -f<br>defrag e: -f<br><br>I saved that as text file then named it hdefrag.bat<br>(f is force)<br><br>then I hit that at night sometimes before sleeping and its a command prompt defrag.<br><br>What I notice, even though I'm doing this in the Xp pro GUI (hitting the bat that is) for some reason that defrags all drives all the way while if I use the GUI one I wake up the next day and the real big files in WoW still have 2 fragments or something<br><br>First time I ran that batch file I had zero fragments on every drive. Something else is that the stupid GUI version only lets you do one drive at a time, instead of specifying to defrag all drives. I think you could do all with scheduling but I don't want to run scheduling just for that, plus I'm on and off the computer at all different times.<br><br><i><span class="sm">Edited, Mon Mar&nbsp;&nbsp;7 15:12:35 2005 by natsuko</span class="sm"></i></p><br /><span class="sm">----------------------------</span><br />Kylathia, 59 Night Elven Priestess, Blackhand<br><a href="http://wow.allakhazam.com/profile.html?8783" target="akztarg">http://wow.allakhazam.com/profile.html?8783</a></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td></tr></table>
